1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:04,099
Speaker 10: Hello, everyone, and welcome
to CON forty-two Golang twenty twenty-six.

2
00:00:04,969 --> 00:00:06,070
My name is Rajnesh Kiran.

3
00:00:06,770 --> 00:00:10,319
I'm a QA engineering manager with Citizens
Property Insurance Corporation in Florida.

4
00:00:11,290 --> 00:00:17,290
Today, I will discuss AI-assisted test
execution and how AI agents can improve

5
00:00:17,320 --> 00:00:22,900
scalability, resilience, and governance
within Go quality engineering ecosystems.

6
00:00:23,669 --> 00:00:25,310
Let us begin with the core capabilities.

7
00:00:25,810 --> 00:00:29,430
AI test agents extend beyond
traditional scripted automation.

8
00:00:30,310 --> 00:00:34,820
They can interpret requirements written
in plain language and convert business

9
00:00:34,850 --> 00:00:37,470
intent into executable validation steps.

10
00:00:38,440 --> 00:00:42,670
They also navigate interfaces
adaptively, making them more

11
00:00:42,670 --> 00:00:45,989
resilient when application
structures or attributes changes.

12
00:00:46,809 --> 00:00:50,880
And importantly, they validate
expected behavior even when

13
00:00:50,909 --> 00:00:52,770
underlying implementations evolve.

14
00:00:53,270 --> 00:00:58,220
So what does current research actually
tell us about these approaches?

15
00:00:58,720 --> 00:01:02,420
Research across enterprise web
systems shows promising results

16
00:01:02,420 --> 00:01:04,770
for AI-assisted testing approaches.

17
00:01:05,380 --> 00:01:09,560
Context-aware locator techniques have
demonstrated better resilience when

18
00:01:10,190 --> 00:01:12,610
DOM structures and identifiers change.

19
00:01:13,580 --> 00:01:18,150
Maintenance effort also shifts away
from fixing locator drift and towards

20
00:01:18,750 --> 00:01:20,950
validating genuine behavioral changes.

21
00:01:21,770 --> 00:01:26,290
At the same time, large-scale
enterprise validation remains limited,

22
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:32,290
especially in regulated industries like
insurance and banking, so adoption must

23
00:01:32,329 --> 00:01:34,450
remain careful and evidence-driven.

24
00:01:35,419 --> 00:01:39,600
This leads to an important principle:
augmentation rather than replacement.

25
00:01:40,100 --> 00:01:46,060
The goal is not replacing go-testing
ecosystems, but existing Go framework

26
00:01:46,220 --> 00:01:49,930
table-driven tests, benchmark
suites, integration harnesses

27
00:01:50,010 --> 00:01:51,399
remain the core execution layer.

28
00:01:51,899 --> 00:01:56,189
AI operates as an augmentation layer
above those systems, introducing

29
00:01:56,229 --> 00:02:00,059
adaptability where it delivers
the highest value, especially in

30
00:02:00,059 --> 00:02:01,699
system and acceptance testing.

31
00:02:02,199 --> 00:02:07,809
However, introducing AI also introduces
new governance requirements, especially

32
00:02:07,809 --> 00:02:10,329
in regulated environments like ours.

33
00:02:10,829 --> 00:02:12,669
Traditional automation is deterministic.

34
00:02:13,169 --> 00:02:16,849
You give an input, you get an output,
there is nothing unpredictable.

35
00:02:17,590 --> 00:02:21,320
AI-assisted systems are
probabilistic, meaning outcomes

36
00:02:21,320 --> 00:02:26,055
may carry varying confidence levels
That makes governance essential.

37
00:02:26,555 --> 00:02:31,055
Organizations must define confidence
thresholds, escalation policies,

38
00:02:31,095 --> 00:02:35,764
and human oversight mechanisms
before deploying AI-driven execution

39
00:02:35,795 --> 00:02:37,415
into regulated environments.

40
00:02:37,915 --> 00:02:41,195
One practical approach is
confidence-based escalation.

41
00:02:41,695 --> 00:02:46,985
A matured AI-assisted testing model
should not produce only binary outcomes.

42
00:02:47,495 --> 00:02:51,895
Instead, confidence level
drives the downstream actions.

43
00:02:52,395 --> 00:02:55,255
High confidence outcomes
may proceed automatically.

44
00:02:55,755 --> 00:02:59,175
Medium confidence cases
triggers engineer review.

45
00:03:00,005 --> 00:03:04,984
Low confidence scenarios escalates
to humans or block releases entirely.

46
00:03:05,484 --> 00:03:08,495
And if the classification
fails, deterministic fallback

47
00:03:08,544 --> 00:03:09,904
execution remains available.

48
00:03:10,404 --> 00:03:13,434
Beyond escalation,
explainability becomes critical.

49
00:03:13,934 --> 00:03:18,224
In regulated industries, test execution
artifacts are compliance evidence as well.

50
00:03:18,914 --> 00:03:23,834
Every AI action should remain explainable,
attributable, and reproducible.

51
00:03:24,694 --> 00:03:28,954
That includes maintaining decision logs,
traceability chains from requirements

52
00:03:28,954 --> 00:03:34,064
through execution, and replayable sessions
for investigation and audit review.

53
00:03:34,564 --> 00:03:37,464
Closely related to this
is safe failure handling.

54
00:03:37,964 --> 00:03:40,894
AI-assisted systems mu-must fail safely.

55
00:03:41,444 --> 00:03:44,844
When confidence drops, the system
should transition through clearly

56
00:03:45,324 --> 00:03:48,694
defined fallback paths rather
than entering undefined states.

57
00:03:49,194 --> 00:03:53,664
That may include pausing for human
input, falling back to deterministic

58
00:03:53,724 --> 00:03:57,144
Go scripts, or generating
escalation tickets automatically.

59
00:03:57,644 --> 00:04:01,364
Now let us connect these concepts
specifically to Go ecosystems.

60
00:04:01,864 --> 00:04:07,344
AI agents integrate naturally into Go
ecosystems because Go already emphasizes

61
00:04:07,344 --> 00:04:09,134
structured testing and observability.

62
00:04:10,024 --> 00:04:12,234
The Go test remains the
source of the truth.

63
00:04:12,924 --> 00:04:16,744
AI layers contribute orchestration,
telemetry, confidence scoring, and

64
00:04:16,774 --> 00:04:20,874
escalation workflows while integrating
cleanly into CI/CD pipelines such as

65
00:04:21,504 --> 00:04:23,914
GitHub Actions, GitLab, or Jenkins.

66
00:04:24,414 --> 00:04:27,614
Another promising area is
learning-based defect prediction.

67
00:04:28,114 --> 00:04:32,834
Learning-based models can analyze
historical execution patterns to predict

68
00:04:33,054 --> 00:04:35,934
where defects are more likely to emerge.

69
00:04:36,394 --> 00:04:41,854
This enables risk-based prioritization,
allowing high-risk test to execute

70
00:04:41,954 --> 00:04:46,524
earlier in the CI pipelines and
reducing time to first failures.

71
00:04:47,524 --> 00:04:50,814
So how should organizations adopt
these capabilities responsibly?

72
00:04:51,314 --> 00:04:54,824
A responsible adoption strategy
should remain phased and incremental.

73
00:04:55,624 --> 00:05:00,974
Organizations can begin in observation
mode, then gradually introduce

74
00:05:01,524 --> 00:05:05,264
augmentation capabilities before
scaling AI-assisted execution

75
00:05:05,304 --> 00:05:07,314
across broader test portfolios.

76
00:05:07,814 --> 00:05:11,844
Governance and evidence collection should
mature alongside technical adoption.

77
00:05:12,344 --> 00:05:14,864
Let me close with a few
take-- key takeaways.

78
00:05:15,364 --> 00:05:20,234
First, AI should augment existing testing
frameworks rather than replacing them.

79
00:05:21,054 --> 00:05:25,584
Second, probablic sy-- prob-probabilistic
systems require explicit governance

80
00:05:25,584 --> 00:05:29,004
through threshold, escalation
paths, and fallback strategies.

81
00:05:29,654 --> 00:05:34,594
Third, explainability and auditability
are essential in regulated industries.

82
00:05:35,524 --> 00:05:39,524
And finally, adoption should
remain incremental and

83
00:05:39,524 --> 00:05:40,834
evidence-dri- evidence-driven.

84
00:05:41,334 --> 00:05:42,064
Thank you very much.

85
00:05:42,564 --> 00:05:46,094
Thank you for attending this session at
CON forty-two Golang twenty twenty-six.

86
00:05:46,774 --> 00:05:50,204
I appreciate your time and interest
in AI-assisted quality engineering.

87
00:05:50,704 --> 00:05:53,864
I would be happy to continue
any conversations further

88
00:05:53,864 --> 00:05:55,464
through LinkedIn or email.

89
00:05:56,164 --> 00:05:56,554
Thank you.

